# Feasibility first (flag manual-labor risk early)

Before starting a **big new ask** — a new asset pipeline, swapping in external/3D/media assets,
a new subsystem, or any multi-day approach — give an **honest feasibility assessment up front**,
scoped to **what an automated agent can actually achieve** without significant human hand-labor.

Labs goal: **minimize manual human labor** (no hand 3D-modeling, rigging, frame-by-frame asset
cleanup, or pixel-pushing). Treat "would this need a human to finish it well?" as a first-class
gating question, not an afterthought discovered three iterations in.

## Do this before investing

1. **State the honest yield.** Will the agent-automatable path plausibly hit the required quality
   bar? Name the parts that would need **manual human intervention** (modeling, rigging, retopo,
   pose-matching, art cleanup) and roughly how much.
2. **Flag low-yield paths explicitly.** If an approach likely needs substantial manual work to look
   right, **say so and recommend against it** before writing the code. Offer the
   lower-labor alternative (use what the source asset already provides, drop the feature, pick a
   different asset that fits the existing pose/rig).
3. **The choice is the user's.** Surface the risk and a recommendation; let the user decide. Do not
   silently start down a multi-iteration path that you expect will require hand-finishing.
4. **Prefer a cheap probe.** When unsure, propose a 1-step spike (one import, one alignment test,
   one screenshot) to falsify the approach fast — before building the full pipeline.

## Trigger examples

- "Swap in / generate a new 3D / media asset and make it match our rig/pose" → check pose/topology
  compatibility **first**; uniform scale/rotate/translate cannot fix a pose or rig mismatch.
- "Repair / patch a flawed source mesh with scripts" → if patches stack into hacks, flag that the
  asset may be the wrong foundation rather than iterating repair scripts.

## Root cause class

`feasibility-misjudged` — heavy investment in a path that needed significant manual human labor to
reach quality; should have been flagged early so the user could choose. See
[`docs/CONTINUOUS_PROCESS_IMPROVEMENT.md`](../../docs/CONTINUOUS_PROCESS_IMPROVEMENT.md).
